Hand hygiene is a widely used intervention and has been shown to effectively reduce the transmission of gastrointestinal infections and respiratory infections (

  26
 ). However, in our systematic review, updating the findings of Wong et al. (

  8
 ), we did not find evidence of a major effect of hand hygiene on laboratory-confirmed influenza virus transmission (
 Figure 1). Nevertheless, hand hygiene might be included in influenza pandemic plans as part of general hygiene and infection prevention.
